<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="392" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,748,1500]" pageId="2" pageNumber="392">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,1304,1327]" pageId="2" pageNumber="392">Comments.</emphasis>
The basal position of the campaniform sensillum on the second antennal segment, the proximity of the posterior pair of ocelli to the compound eyes, and the lateral erosion of abdominal tergite II indicate that this new genus is a member of the Plectrothripini, despite the lack of any glandular reticulation on the sternites. It seems to share most character states with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okajima" authorityYear="1981" box="[374,542,1407,1431]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Chiridurothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="392" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[374,542,1407,1431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="392">Chiridurothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the only species in that genus has a tapering tube that is slightly longer than the head, with the major setae on tergite IX as long as the tube. In contrast, this new species has the tube less than 0.3 as long as the head, and the setae on tergite IX are amongst the shortest recorded in 
<taxonomicName box="[961,1132,1477,1500]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="392" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phlaeothripidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
